00:00:05.429 --> 00:00:06.720
MATTEO VALLONE: Hello everyone.

00:00:06.720 --> 00:00:08.170
My name is Matteo
Vallone, and I work

00:00:08.170 --> 00:00:09.580
in the Google Play
apps and games

00:00:09.580 --> 00:00:10.750
business development team.

00:00:10.750 --> 00:00:12.430
Welcome.

00:00:12.430 --> 00:00:14.420
In my day-to-day
job, I work with some

00:00:14.420 --> 00:00:17.070
of the most successful
apps and games developers,

00:00:17.070 --> 00:00:18.570
and I always think
that there's lots

00:00:18.570 --> 00:00:20.560
to be learned by apps
developers by looking

00:00:20.560 --> 00:00:24.070
at how successful games
developers are built.

00:00:24.070 --> 00:00:26.910
What are the key things
that games developers care

00:00:26.910 --> 00:00:30.910
about when they actually
build their games for success?

00:00:30.910 --> 00:00:32.560
In the next 30, 40
minutes I'll try

00:00:32.560 --> 00:00:35.260
to answer that
question by showing you

00:00:35.260 --> 00:00:37.240
some of the key metrics
that they look at

00:00:37.240 --> 00:00:40.070
and how they go about
and optimize for them.

00:00:40.070 --> 00:00:42.490
I will also try to extrapolate
some rules that you,

00:00:42.490 --> 00:00:44.790
as app developers, can
take in your day-to-day job

00:00:44.790 --> 00:00:48.200
and hopefully use to optimize
your apps and also show you

00:00:48.200 --> 00:00:50.850
some examples of how these
learnings have been applied

00:00:50.850 --> 00:00:53.310
by app developers successfully.

00:00:53.310 --> 00:00:56.670
But before doing that, I
want to address the elephant

00:00:56.670 --> 00:00:59.250
in the room right away.

00:00:59.250 --> 00:01:01.220
Apps and games are
not exactly the same.

00:01:01.220 --> 00:01:03.810
Actually, one key
difference is that it's

00:01:03.810 --> 00:01:07.800
much harder to make money
on apps than it is on games.

00:01:07.800 --> 00:01:09.600
And for the purpose
of this talk,

00:01:09.600 --> 00:01:12.370
the main difference
here is that games

00:01:12.370 --> 00:01:16.947
enjoy much more flexibility
when it comes to monetizing.

00:01:16.947 --> 00:01:18.530
That's because, if
you think about it,

00:01:18.530 --> 00:01:23.750
a game is a virtual world with
virtual currency and items.

00:01:23.750 --> 00:01:25.980
So basically there are
endless possibilities

00:01:25.980 --> 00:01:28.760
in terms of what games
developers can put together

00:01:28.760 --> 00:01:33.040
as monetization mechanics,
bundles, and price points,

00:01:33.040 --> 00:01:36.440
while app developers
have less flexibility.

00:01:36.440 --> 00:01:39.380
They're actually limited by
the services and the goods

00:01:39.380 --> 00:01:43.090
that they are trying to sell
within their app, and so less

00:01:43.090 --> 00:01:45.410
flexibility, less granularity.

00:01:45.410 --> 00:01:47.710
But there's also lots
of common ground,

00:01:47.710 --> 00:01:51.410
and the main key thing in
common is the business model.

00:01:51.410 --> 00:01:53.410
For most apps and games,
the business model

00:01:53.410 --> 00:01:54.920
is a freemium model.

00:01:54.920 --> 00:01:57.530
And if you share
that business model,

00:01:57.530 --> 00:02:00.330
the equation you see here on
the right should always be true.

00:02:00.330 --> 00:02:02.840
Your Cost Per Install,
your CPI, should always

00:02:02.840 --> 00:02:07.430
be lower than the lifetime value
of the users that you bring in.

00:02:07.430 --> 00:02:11.370
And lifetime value is a function
of retention, engagement,

00:02:11.370 --> 00:02:13.060
and monetization.

00:02:13.060 --> 00:02:17.060
Now, in a world where there
is more competition for user

00:02:17.060 --> 00:02:18.910
acquisition and
store visibility,

00:02:18.910 --> 00:02:20.700
the CPI is actually
rising for everyone,

00:02:20.700 --> 00:02:22.080
for both apps and games.

00:02:22.080 --> 00:02:24.350
And that means to make
this equation work,

00:02:24.350 --> 00:02:26.830
you really need to focus
on the right side of it,

00:02:26.830 --> 00:02:29.540
the lifetime value, and
those key metrics that

00:02:29.540 --> 00:02:32.270
drive the lifetime value.

00:02:32.270 --> 00:02:35.710
And among these, really, it
all starts with retention.

00:02:35.710 --> 00:02:37.150
Retention is king.

00:02:37.150 --> 00:02:39.900
These data from mobile
intelligence company Quettra

00:02:39.900 --> 00:02:41.640
show you why.

00:02:41.640 --> 00:02:45.410
These are average
retention curves of apps,

00:02:45.410 --> 00:02:48.750
of games on the left
and apps on the right.

00:02:48.750 --> 00:02:51.410
They are ranked by
daily active users.

00:02:51.410 --> 00:02:53.560
So you see the blue line
represents the top 10

00:02:53.560 --> 00:02:56.410
apps in the world by
daily active users,

00:02:56.410 --> 00:02:59.810
the red line is top 50,
yellow line top 100,

00:02:59.810 --> 00:03:01.830
and green line is top 5,000.

00:03:01.830 --> 00:03:04.720
You see how better
retention always

00:03:04.720 --> 00:03:07.440
drives better performance.

00:03:07.440 --> 00:03:10.690
And games developers
know this very well.

00:03:10.690 --> 00:03:13.340
They actually, before
even launching their game,

00:03:13.340 --> 00:03:15.500
before investing in
user acquisition,

00:03:15.500 --> 00:03:17.670
they spend a lot of
time and resources

00:03:17.670 --> 00:03:20.730
optimizing their game
for this key metric.

00:03:20.730 --> 00:03:23.020
This process is
called soft launching.

00:03:23.020 --> 00:03:25.380
They launch an account
in a few test markets

00:03:25.380 --> 00:03:28.040
or to a beta community,
and they really

00:03:28.040 --> 00:03:32.210
spend time tracking how this
retention works for their game

00:03:32.210 --> 00:03:34.230
and change their
games to the point

00:03:34.230 --> 00:03:37.310
where they're comfortable with
the retention curves they see,

00:03:37.310 --> 00:03:40.000
when they think that this
retention can support

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:43.440
that lifetime value equation
that I showed you before,

00:03:43.440 --> 00:03:46.170
and so that they can
actually invest profitably

00:03:46.170 --> 00:03:48.260
in user acquisition.

00:03:48.260 --> 00:03:50.350
This process is very
rigorous, and it

00:03:50.350 --> 00:03:53.040
requires a lot of
attention, but it

00:03:53.040 --> 00:03:56.500
ensures that the
resources are only

00:03:56.500 --> 00:03:58.250
invested in the right products.

00:03:58.250 --> 00:03:59.810
As a matter of
fact, lots of games

00:03:59.810 --> 00:04:01.560
get killed in this process.

00:04:01.560 --> 00:04:04.147
Also high-visibility ones,
so actually, some of them

00:04:04.147 --> 00:04:05.730
never see the light,
just because they

00:04:05.730 --> 00:04:08.400
don't have good retention.

00:04:08.400 --> 00:04:10.640
If you want to
measure retention,

00:04:10.640 --> 00:04:12.700
you can do so with
Firebase Analytics.

00:04:12.700 --> 00:04:15.300
You have a retention
report that shows you

00:04:15.300 --> 00:04:19.079
not only your retention
curve on the top, but also

00:04:19.079 --> 00:04:21.720
your retention
stats by [? cores ?]

00:04:21.720 --> 00:04:25.800
of users that installed
your app in a given day.

00:04:25.800 --> 00:04:28.790
So you can also track
how, as you release

00:04:28.790 --> 00:04:31.790
newer versions of your app,
and people install them,

00:04:31.790 --> 00:04:35.770
how retention changed
and hopefully improves

00:04:35.770 --> 00:04:37.650
as you optimize for retention.

00:04:40.310 --> 00:04:40.810
All right.

00:04:40.810 --> 00:04:42.940
So lots of common ground.

00:04:42.940 --> 00:04:44.290
Retention is king.

00:04:44.290 --> 00:04:47.340
But I want to share with
you three key rules that you

00:04:47.340 --> 00:04:50.910
can take from games
developers and hopefully

00:04:50.910 --> 00:04:52.840
use to optimize your apps.

00:04:52.840 --> 00:04:56.000
The first one is focusing
on the engagement cliff.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:57.630
What I mean by
engagement cliff is

00:04:57.630 --> 00:05:01.060
shown by the same chart I
showed you before from Quettra,

00:05:01.060 --> 00:05:02.950
the retention curves here.

00:05:02.950 --> 00:05:05.610
They did the thing that
I didn't like before.

00:05:05.610 --> 00:05:09.170
If you look at, it's that
the biggest drop in retention

00:05:09.170 --> 00:05:12.740
happens in the first seven days.

00:05:12.740 --> 00:05:15.030
No matter how
successful the app is,

00:05:15.030 --> 00:05:18.320
you see that that's
where retention really

00:05:18.320 --> 00:05:19.310
drops dramatically.

00:05:19.310 --> 00:05:22.070
After that, all curves
tend to flatten.

00:05:22.070 --> 00:05:24.260
So really, the apps
that are doing a better

00:05:24.260 --> 00:05:26.400
job in terms of
retention are doing

00:05:26.400 --> 00:05:27.870
that in the first seven days.

00:05:27.870 --> 00:05:30.400
That's where you win.

00:05:30.400 --> 00:05:34.350
Now, depending on what
type of app you have,

00:05:34.350 --> 00:05:37.910
your day-seven average
retention can vary.

00:05:37.910 --> 00:05:41.010
You see here on the
right average retention,

00:05:41.010 --> 00:05:44.040
day-seven retention, for
different categories of apps.

00:05:44.040 --> 00:05:47.390
So it varies between 40%
for news and magazines

00:05:47.390 --> 00:05:49.810
to 15% for photography.

00:05:49.810 --> 00:05:54.990
But that means that between
60% and 85% of users

00:05:54.990 --> 00:05:57.170
are lost in those
first seven days.

00:05:57.170 --> 00:06:00.940
So clearly, lots of impact in
addressing those first seven

00:06:00.940 --> 00:06:01.980
days.

00:06:01.980 --> 00:06:06.750
And that's because users
download lots of apps,

00:06:06.750 --> 00:06:07.980
and they try them.

00:06:07.980 --> 00:06:09.700
And during those
first few experiences,

00:06:09.700 --> 00:06:12.210
they actually decide whether
they want to keep using them.

00:06:12.210 --> 00:06:13.940
Or otherwise they
forgot about them,

00:06:13.940 --> 00:06:15.640
so sometimes they
uninstall them.

00:06:15.640 --> 00:06:19.990
So really, addressing that
specific experience-- that is,

00:06:19.990 --> 00:06:23.990
between learning about your
app, being comfortable with it,

00:06:23.990 --> 00:06:26.560
and deciding to
actually keep using it--

00:06:26.560 --> 00:06:29.850
is the most important part.

00:06:29.850 --> 00:06:31.870
Games know this very well.

00:06:31.870 --> 00:06:34.100
They actually face a very
steep engagement cliff,

00:06:34.100 --> 00:06:36.710
which is you have to
learn how the game works.

00:06:36.710 --> 00:06:39.930
You have to learn new rules,
you have to learn new mechanics,

00:06:39.930 --> 00:06:42.260
you have to understand
why you should go

00:06:42.260 --> 00:06:43.950
through all these challenges.

00:06:43.950 --> 00:06:46.530
You need to care about it also.

00:06:46.530 --> 00:06:51.410
And that part of the experience
is normally the tutorial.

00:06:51.410 --> 00:06:54.260
Games spend a lot of
resources and time

00:06:54.260 --> 00:06:57.460
optimizing the tutorial, because
they know how critical it is.

00:06:57.460 --> 00:07:00.140
I want to play a video,
an except of a video,

00:07:00.140 --> 00:07:01.890
that we shot with Pixelberry.

00:07:01.890 --> 00:07:04.790
It was a very successful
game developer,

00:07:04.790 --> 00:07:07.500
and it's particularly
good with their tutorials.

00:07:07.500 --> 00:07:09.860
They have more than
75% of users that

00:07:09.860 --> 00:07:13.650
start one of their tutorials
actually complete them.

00:07:13.650 --> 00:07:16.624
So let me play the video here.

00:07:16.624 --> 00:07:17.290
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:07:17.290 --> 00:07:20.410
-Players coming in, we hit
them with story right away,

00:07:20.410 --> 00:07:23.010
and we try and do
it in a way where

00:07:23.010 --> 00:07:24.350
it's a little more natural.

00:07:24.350 --> 00:07:26.930
We are cognizant that a
lot of people playing games

00:07:26.930 --> 00:07:30.100
on mobile phones may not
want to read too much text,

00:07:30.100 --> 00:07:33.575
so we try to ease
players into that.

00:07:33.575 --> 00:07:36.120
But by the time they
finish our tutorial,

00:07:36.120 --> 00:07:37.960
we're hoping that
they're already caught up

00:07:37.960 --> 00:07:39.140
in the lives of
these characters,

00:07:39.140 --> 00:07:40.940
and they want to learn more
about their backstories

00:07:40.940 --> 00:07:42.080
and what's going on.

00:07:42.080 --> 00:07:44.440
-I think it is
important to give people

00:07:44.440 --> 00:07:46.539
kind of that sense of
progression in a game,

00:07:46.539 --> 00:07:48.080
especially in mobile
games, because I

00:07:48.080 --> 00:07:51.460
think with a lot of games,
you can reach a certain point

00:07:51.460 --> 00:07:53.336
where you're just
repeating the same actions,

00:07:53.336 --> 00:07:55.793
and you want to feel like you're
doing something different.

00:07:55.793 --> 00:07:57.950
And I think story is a
great way of differentiating

00:07:57.950 --> 00:08:00.774
that and saying, oh, now you're
dealing with a new villain,

00:08:00.774 --> 00:08:02.940
or now you're dealing with
new issue that's come up.

00:08:02.940 --> 00:08:04.040
[END PLAYBACK]

00:08:04.040 --> 00:08:06.600
MATTEO VALLONE: So they
talk about two key things.

00:08:06.600 --> 00:08:08.220
One is the story.

00:08:08.220 --> 00:08:11.190
The story for their
game is the key element,

00:08:11.190 --> 00:08:13.730
the key value that
you should care

00:08:13.730 --> 00:08:15.470
about when you play this game.

00:08:15.470 --> 00:08:17.650
And they want to
make sure that you

00:08:17.650 --> 00:08:21.400
start experiencing the story
from the first experience.

00:08:21.400 --> 00:08:24.340
Why should the player
care about this game?

00:08:24.340 --> 00:08:26.650
The second thing they
talk about is progression,

00:08:26.650 --> 00:08:29.040
the sense of progression
that should always

00:08:29.040 --> 00:08:30.950
be present in games.

00:08:30.950 --> 00:08:33.610
And if you think about it,
this goes beyond the tutorial.

00:08:33.610 --> 00:08:35.440
It's actually what a game is.

00:08:35.440 --> 00:08:37.679
It always presents you
with a new challenge.

00:08:37.679 --> 00:08:40.262
That challenge, though,
shouldn't be too challenging.

00:08:40.262 --> 00:08:42.470
Otherwise, you're frustrated,
and you leave the game.

00:08:42.470 --> 00:08:43.928
But also, it
shouldn't be too easy.

00:08:43.928 --> 00:08:47.040
Otherwise, you get bored,
and you also leave the game.

00:08:47.040 --> 00:08:50.840
And so games think
a lot about that,

00:08:50.840 --> 00:08:53.940
and this is an example
of how they look at it.

00:08:53.940 --> 00:08:58.430
Playdots, another
successful game developer,

00:08:58.430 --> 00:09:01.530
built this chart for their
game called Two Dots.

00:09:01.530 --> 00:09:04.410
And the chart is lots of dots,
and those dots are actually

00:09:04.410 --> 00:09:05.740
levels in the game.

00:09:05.740 --> 00:09:08.460
And those levels are
mapped along two variables.

00:09:08.460 --> 00:09:11.740
One is the revenue per player
in that specific level,

00:09:11.740 --> 00:09:13.920
and the other one is the
lapse rate in that level.

00:09:13.920 --> 00:09:17.430
So how many people left
the game in that level?

00:09:17.430 --> 00:09:20.330
This gives you an idea about
how frustrating and challenging

00:09:20.330 --> 00:09:22.696
the level is and also
how actually engaging

00:09:22.696 --> 00:09:24.070
and how much people
actually want

00:09:24.070 --> 00:09:27.160
to spend money in that level.

00:09:27.160 --> 00:09:30.970
By optimizing the difficulty
level of the levels--

00:09:30.970 --> 00:09:35.090
sorry for-- below the
red line, they actually

00:09:35.090 --> 00:09:37.010
manage to improve
not only conversion,

00:09:37.010 --> 00:09:40.320
but also average
revenue per paying user.

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:42.780
So progression is
very important.

00:09:42.780 --> 00:09:44.600
But this is very
specific to games,

00:09:44.600 --> 00:09:49.700
so let's try to extrapolate
some learnings for apps.

00:09:49.700 --> 00:09:52.510
Climbing the
engagement cliff is all

00:09:52.510 --> 00:09:54.830
about recognizing that
those first seven days are

00:09:54.830 --> 00:09:57.930
very important and
also quite difficult

00:09:57.930 --> 00:09:59.830
for a user to go through them.

00:09:59.830 --> 00:10:02.320
There's lots of
things happening,

00:10:02.320 --> 00:10:06.910
and really, the value of your
app is not clear to them yet.

00:10:06.910 --> 00:10:08.660
So the first thing
you should focus on

00:10:08.660 --> 00:10:11.720
is finding that key feature
that, without much engagement,

00:10:11.720 --> 00:10:15.010
provides value to the user--
something that can give them

00:10:15.010 --> 00:10:17.710
a wow effect, or something
that can convince them

00:10:17.710 --> 00:10:19.590
that they should stick around.

00:10:19.590 --> 00:10:23.270
And it shouldn't require
too much for them

00:10:23.270 --> 00:10:24.800
to actually unlock that.

00:10:24.800 --> 00:10:26.550
So present that straight away.

00:10:26.550 --> 00:10:29.970
The second thing is defining
those activation moments,

00:10:29.970 --> 00:10:32.530
those things, those steps
in that engagement cliff,

00:10:32.530 --> 00:10:35.670
that you need the
user to go through.

00:10:35.670 --> 00:10:38.910
It could be signing
in, uploading something

00:10:38.910 --> 00:10:41.200
about themselves,
adding some friends.

00:10:41.200 --> 00:10:44.000
Whatever key action,
activation moment,

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:48.430
you need them to do to fully
unlock the value of your app

00:10:48.430 --> 00:10:51.080
and start using it to
its full potential.

00:10:51.080 --> 00:10:52.770
Those are the
activation moments.

00:10:52.770 --> 00:10:54.310
You should make
sure at that point

00:10:54.310 --> 00:10:56.920
that those are
presented gradually,

00:10:56.920 --> 00:11:00.680
with a gradual investment
from a user perspective,

00:11:00.680 --> 00:11:02.970
so that the user
is not overwhelmed.

00:11:02.970 --> 00:11:04.810
They feel the sense
of progression,

00:11:04.810 --> 00:11:06.940
they're going in
a direction, they

00:11:06.940 --> 00:11:10.070
understand why you are asking
them to do these things,

00:11:10.070 --> 00:11:12.860
and they're actually
gradually unlocking

00:11:12.860 --> 00:11:14.530
the value of your app.

00:11:14.530 --> 00:11:17.260
As part of that-- for
example, if you're

00:11:17.260 --> 00:11:20.930
requiring them to sign in-- you
should treat that as a service.

00:11:20.930 --> 00:11:24.120
You should show them
the value of doing that

00:11:24.120 --> 00:11:26.530
before asking them to do it.

00:11:26.530 --> 00:11:28.490
This is, again, in that
sense of progression

00:11:28.490 --> 00:11:31.470
of unlocking that value,
showing them the value

00:11:31.470 --> 00:11:34.050
first, and then asking
them to do something.

00:11:34.050 --> 00:11:36.730
Also, if you have pay
walls, you should carefully

00:11:36.730 --> 00:11:39.770
manage the appearance of them
in those first seven days.

00:11:39.770 --> 00:11:43.270
Again, the user doesn't really
know exactly the full value

00:11:43.270 --> 00:11:44.470
of your app yet.

00:11:44.470 --> 00:11:47.632
You probably don't want to
overwhelm them and ask them

00:11:47.632 --> 00:11:52.400
also about paying until they're
fully comfortable with the app,

00:11:52.400 --> 00:11:55.030
and they've actually
unlocked the full value.

00:11:55.030 --> 00:11:58.240
You can optimize along
these lines using, again,

00:11:58.240 --> 00:11:59.920
Firebase Analytics.

00:11:59.920 --> 00:12:02.150
The final report
here can help you.

00:12:02.150 --> 00:12:05.820
In the final report, you
can create any custom event

00:12:05.820 --> 00:12:06.760
that you want.

00:12:06.760 --> 00:12:10.320
It could be signing in,
uploading a photo, whatever

00:12:10.320 --> 00:12:13.570
process, activation moment you
need the user to go through,

00:12:13.570 --> 00:12:16.880
can be defined in
the final reports.

00:12:16.880 --> 00:12:21.940
And you can track how many
users start that process or task

00:12:21.940 --> 00:12:23.190
and complete it.

00:12:23.190 --> 00:12:26.190
So you can also put
them in a sequence

00:12:26.190 --> 00:12:29.980
and see, as a funnel,
where the user gets stuck.

00:12:29.980 --> 00:12:31.720
You can see how
many people started

00:12:31.720 --> 00:12:34.210
one action, the second
action, the third action,

00:12:34.210 --> 00:12:37.820
and identify those roadblocks
that stopped them from actually

00:12:37.820 --> 00:12:40.050
going through all of them.

00:12:40.050 --> 00:12:41.510
So a very powerful tool.

00:12:41.510 --> 00:12:43.820
And now I want to show
you a couple of examples

00:12:43.820 --> 00:12:47.710
of apps that have implemented
this rule successfully

00:12:47.710 --> 00:12:48.590
in their app.

00:12:48.590 --> 00:12:50.610
The first one is OkCupid.

00:12:50.610 --> 00:12:52.390
OkCupid is a dating app.

00:12:52.390 --> 00:12:54.570
Dating apps are a great
example of engagement cliff,

00:12:54.570 --> 00:12:57.540
because before you can
actually use a dating app,

00:12:57.540 --> 00:12:59.290
you have to do lots of things.

00:12:59.290 --> 00:13:03.200
You have to sign in, you have to
write something about yourself,

00:13:03.200 --> 00:13:05.100
you have to upload
a photo of yourself,

00:13:05.100 --> 00:13:07.170
you have to answer some
questions in some cases,

00:13:07.170 --> 00:13:11.350
like in OkCupid's case, and you
have to start liking people.

00:13:11.350 --> 00:13:12.200
So lots of things.

00:13:12.200 --> 00:13:16.010
And OkCupid recently redesigned
their whole onboarding

00:13:16.010 --> 00:13:20.350
experience to make it more
gradual and step-by-step.

00:13:20.350 --> 00:13:23.780
Also, they made each task
more enjoyable, skippable,

00:13:23.780 --> 00:13:26.650
and they provided good
positive feedback to the user

00:13:26.650 --> 00:13:29.740
as they went through these
tasks, again announcing

00:13:29.740 --> 00:13:32.350
this sense of progression
that the user had

00:13:32.350 --> 00:13:36.050
to feel to actually
complete these tasks.

00:13:36.050 --> 00:13:41.070
As a result, they got 21%
better day-seven retention.

00:13:41.070 --> 00:13:45.730
This means that after seven
days, they had 20% more users.

00:13:45.730 --> 00:13:48.490
Same cost per install,
after seven days

00:13:48.490 --> 00:13:50.800
they had 20% more users.

00:13:50.800 --> 00:13:52.620
How they did this?

00:13:52.620 --> 00:13:55.280
This is how it looked
before the redesign.

00:13:55.280 --> 00:13:58.390
So you see they're asking you to
write something about yourself,

00:13:58.390 --> 00:14:01.710
to upload a photo, to
answer some questions.

00:14:01.710 --> 00:14:04.090
And this is all presented
in a series of modal windows

00:14:04.090 --> 00:14:06.070
with no clear sequencing.

00:14:06.070 --> 00:14:09.360
Also, if you start one of
these activities-- for example,

00:14:09.360 --> 00:14:14.240
answering the question--
you see here on the right,

00:14:14.240 --> 00:14:18.040
those are presented
all together.

00:14:18.040 --> 00:14:20.305
Doesn't look very fun
to go through them.

00:14:20.305 --> 00:14:22.820
It's quite actually
overwhelming.

00:14:22.820 --> 00:14:25.740
This is how it looks
after the redesign.

00:14:25.740 --> 00:14:27.620
The first and only
thing you need

00:14:27.620 --> 00:14:29.980
to care about after
