with people that you might like.

00:15:13.941 --> 00:15:14.440
All right.

00:15:14.440 --> 00:15:15.450
That was in one example.

00:15:15.450 --> 00:15:18.200
The other example is Freeletics.

00:15:18.200 --> 00:15:19.730
Freeletics is a
fitness app, and I

00:15:19.730 --> 00:15:22.810
think that's probably the best
example of an engagement cliff.

00:15:22.810 --> 00:15:25.450
When you download a
fitness app, you're

00:15:25.450 --> 00:15:28.090
probably not doing fitness yet.

00:15:28.090 --> 00:15:31.890
So the fitness app needs to
convince you to go to the gym

00:15:31.890 --> 00:15:34.160
and actually do fitness.

00:15:34.160 --> 00:15:36.900
It's not enough if you just
download the app, right?

00:15:36.900 --> 00:15:38.640
So that's the first
key challenge.

00:15:38.640 --> 00:15:41.840
The second challenge is,
when you download the app,

00:15:41.840 --> 00:15:44.810
and you actually go to
the gym to use your app,

00:15:44.810 --> 00:15:46.480
there might be some
time in between.

00:15:46.480 --> 00:15:48.610
And what do you do with the app?

00:15:48.610 --> 00:15:51.160
And in those days that
you're not going to the gym,

00:15:51.160 --> 00:15:52.640
you might forget
about it, or you

00:15:52.640 --> 00:15:54.540
might find another app, right?

00:15:54.540 --> 00:15:58.170
So how do you keep users
engaged in that time frame?

00:15:58.170 --> 00:16:00.620
And that's common
to other verticals,

00:16:00.620 --> 00:16:03.630
but definitely fitness is
a good example of that.

00:16:03.630 --> 00:16:06.190
Freeletics addressed
these challenges

00:16:06.190 --> 00:16:08.800
by making sure that their
onboarding experience felt

00:16:08.800 --> 00:16:11.850
more personal from the
first minute you started.

00:16:11.850 --> 00:16:14.640
You're building some
key attainable goal

00:16:14.640 --> 00:16:18.380
that is personalized
based on your input

00:16:18.380 --> 00:16:23.810
and that you feel more empowered
to actually go and achieve.

00:16:23.810 --> 00:16:27.190
As a result, they obtained
47% better day-one retention,

00:16:27.190 --> 00:16:31.555
so almost 50% more users,
after the first day,

00:16:31.555 --> 00:16:33.340
kept using the app.

00:16:33.340 --> 00:16:34.330
How they did that?

00:16:34.330 --> 00:16:37.590
This is how it looked
before their redesign.

00:16:37.590 --> 00:16:39.220
So basically, you
download the app,

00:16:39.220 --> 00:16:42.340
you get a few cards
of what the app does.

00:16:42.340 --> 00:16:45.400
And right after, you
are asked to sign in.

00:16:45.400 --> 00:16:46.940
And after signing
in, you're asked

00:16:46.940 --> 00:16:49.610
to obtain their newsletter.

00:16:49.610 --> 00:16:52.770
After that, you're
considered a registered user,

00:16:52.770 --> 00:16:54.980
and you can start
browsing the app,

00:16:54.980 --> 00:16:58.840
understanding what it does for
you, and taking next steps,

00:16:58.840 --> 00:17:00.060
basically.

00:17:00.060 --> 00:17:02.800
What they did is
introducing this.

00:17:02.800 --> 00:17:04.760
After those first few
cards that I showed you,

00:17:04.760 --> 00:17:08.730
the photos about the app, the
thing they do is they ask you,

00:17:08.730 --> 00:17:10.480
are you are a male or a female?

00:17:10.480 --> 00:17:13.300
Let's start understanding
who you are.

00:17:13.300 --> 00:17:15.356
And once you answer
that first question,

00:17:15.356 --> 00:17:16.980
they start personalizing
the appearance

00:17:16.980 --> 00:17:18.063
of the rest of the screen.

00:17:18.063 --> 00:17:19.926
So if you're a male,
you see a male picture.

00:17:19.926 --> 00:17:21.800
If you're a female, you
see a female picture.

00:17:21.800 --> 00:17:24.180
And then they ask you,
what's your fitness level?

00:17:24.180 --> 00:17:26.550
They also tell you why
they're asking you this.

00:17:26.550 --> 00:17:28.480
It's because they're
starting to know you.

00:17:28.480 --> 00:17:30.330
They're starting
to learn about what

00:17:30.330 --> 00:17:32.820
you care about so that they
can build your first workout

00:17:32.820 --> 00:17:33.980
experience.

00:17:33.980 --> 00:17:36.720
Clear value, they're
treating this information

00:17:36.720 --> 00:17:38.850
as a service for you,
and they're giving you

00:17:38.850 --> 00:17:40.890
a sense of progression.

00:17:40.890 --> 00:17:43.370
Third step is what's your goal?

00:17:43.370 --> 00:17:44.760
Do you want to lose weight?

00:17:44.760 --> 00:17:46.550
Do you want to build muscles?

00:17:46.550 --> 00:17:48.650
Why do you want to do fitness?

00:17:48.650 --> 00:17:52.440
After that, only after that,
you are asked to sign in.

00:17:52.440 --> 00:17:54.820
Now you understand the
value of signing in.

00:17:54.820 --> 00:17:56.620
You're storing this
information, and you're

00:17:56.620 --> 00:17:59.930
allowing them to build your
personal workout experience.

00:17:59.930 --> 00:18:01.910
Much different than
just asking people

00:18:01.910 --> 00:18:05.970
to sign in without knowing
why I should sign in.

00:18:05.970 --> 00:18:08.360
Then they ask you if you want
to join their newsletter,

00:18:08.360 --> 00:18:10.990
but again, you
understand why now.

00:18:10.990 --> 00:18:14.210
They are going to send you
personal recommendations, based

00:18:14.210 --> 00:18:17.460
on your goals, to your inbox.

00:18:17.460 --> 00:18:19.720
After that, the
last thing you see

00:18:19.720 --> 00:18:22.160
is a feedback screen
that tells you

00:18:22.160 --> 00:18:25.610
that they're actually building
your first workout experience.

00:18:25.610 --> 00:18:28.220
So again, it's much
more compelling

00:18:28.220 --> 00:18:31.330
to go through the first
experience of this app,

00:18:31.330 --> 00:18:33.860
even if you're not at the
gym, because you are doing

00:18:33.860 --> 00:18:35.960
something in that direction.

00:18:35.960 --> 00:18:39.680
There is a progression toward
that first gym experience.

00:18:39.680 --> 00:18:43.770
And also, after this, you
feel that you have some goal,

00:18:43.770 --> 00:18:45.940
and probably you are more
motivated to actually go

00:18:45.940 --> 00:18:47.450
to the gym in and do it.

00:18:47.450 --> 00:18:50.010
And actually, this can
be seen in the impact

00:18:50.010 --> 00:18:54.977
that they had also on day-three
retention, which was 17% better

00:18:54.977 --> 00:18:56.060
than the previous version.

00:18:56.060 --> 00:18:59.630
So even after this
first experience,

00:18:59.630 --> 00:19:01.629
people were actually
using the app more,

00:19:01.629 --> 00:19:03.170
and that's probably
because they were

00:19:03.170 --> 00:19:05.720
more motivated to go to
the gym and actually do

00:19:05.720 --> 00:19:08.610
what you do with a fitness
app, which is fitness.

00:19:08.610 --> 00:19:10.520
All right.

00:19:10.520 --> 00:19:13.790
That was onboarding, and
hopefully at this point,

00:19:13.790 --> 00:19:15.500
your users are
retained, onboarded,

00:19:15.500 --> 00:19:17.250
and they understand
the value of your app,

00:19:17.250 --> 00:19:19.310
and you want to monetize them.

00:19:19.310 --> 00:19:21.750
The next two rules
are about that.

00:19:21.750 --> 00:19:24.530
The first one,
embracing your app's

00:19:24.530 --> 00:19:26.850
multiple personality disorder.

00:19:26.850 --> 00:19:29.320
This is what I mean by that.

00:19:29.320 --> 00:19:32.990
This is an average
revenue distribution

00:19:32.990 --> 00:19:35.690
curve for an average game.

00:19:35.690 --> 00:19:38.930
No matter how
successful a game is,

00:19:38.930 --> 00:19:42.090
lots of people will
not spend a dime in it.

00:19:42.090 --> 00:19:44.460
And even among the
ones that spend,

00:19:44.460 --> 00:19:47.960
there are very different amounts
that they're going to spend.

00:19:47.960 --> 00:19:49.850
A big segment might
spend very little;

00:19:49.850 --> 00:19:52.640
a small segment might
spend lots of money.

00:19:52.640 --> 00:19:56.010
And then there are other
segments in between.

00:19:56.010 --> 00:20:00.720
Recognizing, understanding
what each user is going

00:20:00.720 --> 00:20:02.860
to potentially
spend in your game;

00:20:02.860 --> 00:20:05.280
and how they like to
spend; what is the value

00:20:05.280 --> 00:20:09.290
perception that they have; what
is their propensity to spend;

00:20:09.290 --> 00:20:11.430
and targeting them
based on what you

00:20:11.430 --> 00:20:15.770
know about them with special,
custom, in-app purchase

00:20:15.770 --> 00:20:19.630
offers-- that's the key to
achieve much better conversion

00:20:19.630 --> 00:20:21.570
and revenue per user.

00:20:21.570 --> 00:20:24.550
This is an example of how a
game developer looks at this.

00:20:24.550 --> 00:20:27.800
This is Wooga, and it's
just one way to look at it.

00:20:27.800 --> 00:20:31.430
They segment their users
along two variables.

00:20:31.430 --> 00:20:34.830
One is progression in the
game and the other one

00:20:34.830 --> 00:20:37.000
is spending level.

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:39.505
So for each segment
you see in blue,

00:20:39.505 --> 00:20:42.050
they have a different
way to target them,

00:20:42.050 --> 00:20:46.980
different offers that
they can trigger to

00:20:46.980 --> 00:20:48.720
for that specific segment.

00:20:48.720 --> 00:20:51.540
For example, if
you're a new player,

00:20:51.540 --> 00:20:53.720
they offer you a starter pack.

00:20:53.720 --> 00:20:56.490
Now, if you buy this, you
become an early spender.

00:20:56.490 --> 00:20:57.990
You're not just a
new player, you're

00:20:57.990 --> 00:20:59.670
someone who spends early.

00:20:59.670 --> 00:21:03.000
And they try to upsell
with some other offer.

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:06.324
If you buy that, then you
become an early heavy spender.

00:21:06.324 --> 00:21:07.740
You're in a different
segment now,

00:21:07.740 --> 00:21:09.781
and they might target you
with a different offer.

00:21:09.781 --> 00:21:12.610
If you don't buy, you
might become a mid spender,

00:21:12.610 --> 00:21:16.620
so later in the game, they
know which steps you took,

00:21:16.620 --> 00:21:19.710
and they will target you with
a different discounted offer

00:21:19.710 --> 00:21:21.200
based on that segment.

00:21:21.200 --> 00:21:23.880
If you don't buy then, you
might become a late spender,

00:21:23.880 --> 00:21:26.210
so they will target later,
even later in the game,

00:21:26.210 --> 00:21:29.170
with an even different offer.

00:21:29.170 --> 00:21:32.480
That's a very simple but very
effective way to look at.

00:21:32.480 --> 00:21:34.700
A more advanced and
complicated but very effective

00:21:34.700 --> 00:21:38.120
way is this other
example from Space Ape.

00:21:38.120 --> 00:21:41.260
What they do is that they
analyze their players' behavior

00:21:41.260 --> 00:21:45.170
in those first seven days, and
they predict the lifetime value

00:21:45.170 --> 00:21:48.170
that those users will bring
to the game for the rest

00:21:48.170 --> 00:21:49.690
of their life in the game.

00:21:49.690 --> 00:21:52.820
And they look at how they
spend, what they spend on,

00:21:52.820 --> 00:21:55.390
and also how they like to spend.

00:21:55.390 --> 00:21:57.600
And then they target them
with different offers.

00:21:57.600 --> 00:22:01.760
By doing this, they achieve two
times better conversion then

00:22:01.760 --> 00:22:05.200
having a one-size-fits-all
approach.

00:22:05.200 --> 00:22:07.600
This is how it works.

00:22:07.600 --> 00:22:09.290
Players play.

00:22:09.290 --> 00:22:11.230
For the first seven
days, Space Ape

00:22:11.230 --> 00:22:13.980
analyzes their behavior,
their spending pattern.

00:22:13.980 --> 00:22:16.350
And based on their
lifetime-value models,

00:22:16.350 --> 00:22:22.410
they predict how much value
each user will bring to the game

00:22:22.410 --> 00:22:24.310
and how they like to spend.

00:22:24.310 --> 00:22:27.730
And they assign each user
to a separate segment.

00:22:27.730 --> 00:22:31.020
Here you see an example
of two segments, just

00:22:31.020 --> 00:22:32.360
to give you an idea.

00:22:32.360 --> 00:22:35.650
The first segment has
medium lifetime value,

00:22:35.650 --> 00:22:37.880
but they actually spent a lot.

00:22:37.880 --> 00:22:41.620
Only they spent in one
go, and they're not

00:22:41.620 --> 00:22:43.070
very frequent buyers.

00:22:43.070 --> 00:22:45.090
They might not
spend again, or they

00:22:45.090 --> 00:22:48.940
will spend, but at a later
stage, not very frequently.

00:22:48.940 --> 00:22:53.160
The second group, they spend
less in a single instance,

00:22:53.160 --> 00:22:55.110
but they're more frequent.

00:22:55.110 --> 00:22:57.030
They're going to keep
coming and spending.

00:22:57.030 --> 00:22:59.380
So their lifetime
value is higher;

00:22:59.380 --> 00:23:02.490
it's just that they like to
spend in a different way.

00:23:02.490 --> 00:23:06.330
These two segments will see
different offers in the game.

00:23:06.330 --> 00:23:08.940
The first one will
see a big bundle

00:23:08.940 --> 00:23:11.150
with a very high price point.

00:23:11.150 --> 00:23:13.670
Lots of value in it,
but that's the way

00:23:13.670 --> 00:23:15.410
to convert these people.

00:23:15.410 --> 00:23:20.850
They're not scared about
seeing a big price point,

00:23:20.850 --> 00:23:24.110
but they also want more value,
because they're not probably

00:23:24.110 --> 00:23:25.740
not going to come
back and spend later.

00:23:25.740 --> 00:23:29.300
And that's what you should
focus on as a developer.

00:23:29.300 --> 00:23:35.110
Now, the second segment will
see a much smaller bundle,

00:23:35.110 --> 00:23:37.550
and that will make
them comfortable,

00:23:37.550 --> 00:23:39.830
and they will probably
convert with that.

00:23:39.830 --> 00:23:42.210
But also, the developer
knows that they will probably

00:23:42.210 --> 00:23:43.690
come back and buy more.

00:23:43.690 --> 00:23:48.330
So overall, their lifetime
value will be higher.

00:23:48.330 --> 00:23:51.780
OK, let's generalize and
extrapolate some rules that you

00:23:51.780 --> 00:23:54.060
can take as app developers.

00:23:54.060 --> 00:23:57.560
You need to recognize
that users will

00:23:57.560 --> 00:24:00.360
have a very different value
perception of your app.

00:24:00.360 --> 00:24:03.410
And no matter how successful
you are, no matter how relevant

00:24:03.410 --> 00:24:06.180
your app is, they will
have a different propensity

00:24:06.180 --> 00:24:09.350
to spend and also a
different way to spend.

00:24:09.350 --> 00:24:13.175
If you can recognize that,
segment your user base based

00:24:13.175 --> 00:24:17.120
on this, and target them
with specific, custom in-app

00:24:17.120 --> 00:24:21.100
purchase offers, then
you can definitely

00:24:21.100 --> 00:24:25.260
achieve a much better
conversion and revenue per user.

