Here we use it to build a high
lifetime value segment that

00:24:38.790 --> 00:24:42.400
actually has a very
small single price

00:24:42.400 --> 00:24:45.330
point but frequent
purchase behavior,

00:24:45.330 --> 00:24:48.230
and a medium lifetime
value segment

00:24:48.230 --> 00:24:52.670
that has a high single
price point but not frequent

00:24:52.670 --> 00:24:54.420
spend behavior.

00:24:54.420 --> 00:24:56.520
This is all done with
Firebase Analytics

00:24:56.520 --> 00:25:00.890
using events and attributes
that the users have.

00:25:00.890 --> 00:25:04.170
And based on this, you can
track how they perform.

00:25:04.170 --> 00:25:06.200
Any chart in Firebase
Analytics will show you

00:25:06.200 --> 00:25:08.570
these two different
segments and how they behave

00:25:08.570 --> 00:25:10.119
so you can better study them.

00:25:10.119 --> 00:25:11.660
But now what you
can do, you can also

00:25:11.660 --> 00:25:15.980
target them with different
offers using remote config

00:25:15.980 --> 00:25:17.760
in Firebase.

00:25:17.760 --> 00:25:20.000
The way it works, for
example, let's say

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:22.630
you sell a subscription.

00:25:22.630 --> 00:25:24.130
You're a newspaper
or a fitness app,

00:25:24.130 --> 00:25:26.050
and you sell a subscription.

00:25:26.050 --> 00:25:30.540
For the first segment, the one
with high single spend points

00:25:30.540 --> 00:25:34.530
but not very frequent,
you can build a promotion

00:25:34.530 --> 00:25:36.590
for your annual subscription.

00:25:36.590 --> 00:25:38.890
These guys are comfortable
spending a lot,

00:25:38.890 --> 00:25:41.364
but they don't want to
be bothered every month.

00:25:41.364 --> 00:25:43.280
They will buy an annual
subscription probably,

00:25:43.280 --> 00:25:46.020
so you can have a heavily
discounted annual subscription

00:25:46.020 --> 00:25:47.240
for them.

00:25:47.240 --> 00:25:50.890
And for the other group
with a higher lifetime

00:25:50.890 --> 00:25:54.010
value but single
price point lower,

00:25:54.010 --> 00:25:57.080
you can have a discount
on a monthly subscription.

00:25:57.080 --> 00:25:59.290
So the price point
will be lower,

00:25:59.290 --> 00:26:01.260
but they're more
comfortable doing that,

00:26:01.260 --> 00:26:04.620
and you can target
them with this offer.

00:26:04.620 --> 00:26:08.480
Again, it's very easy to
do this with remote config.

00:26:08.480 --> 00:26:09.750
And you don't need to code.

00:26:09.750 --> 00:26:11.990
You just need to go
through the options,

00:26:11.990 --> 00:26:15.410
and it will be very easy.

00:26:15.410 --> 00:26:19.000
This works on in-app
purchases for virtual goods.

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:21.150
It also works for
physical goods.

00:26:21.150 --> 00:26:23.260
So if you have an
e-commerce app, for example,

00:26:23.260 --> 00:26:24.700
this example applies to you.

00:26:24.700 --> 00:26:28.380
This is Wish, a very
successful e-commerce app.

00:26:28.380 --> 00:26:31.049
And they basically,
in their screen,

00:26:31.049 --> 00:26:32.840
they show products to
users that they think

00:26:32.840 --> 00:26:34.590
they might want to buy.

00:26:34.590 --> 00:26:36.500
And they also apply
the same concept.

00:26:36.500 --> 00:26:39.730
They show less expensive
items to users that

00:26:39.730 --> 00:26:41.280
have shown less engagement.

00:26:41.280 --> 00:26:43.210
Maybe they haven't
bought anything yet,

00:26:43.210 --> 00:26:45.168
they started using the
app, or they're just not

00:26:45.168 --> 00:26:46.300
that much engaged.

00:26:46.300 --> 00:26:49.460
And once they see that the
users are more engaged,

00:26:49.460 --> 00:26:51.870
they spend maybe
a couple of times,

00:26:51.870 --> 00:26:55.990
they start showing them
more expensive products.

00:26:55.990 --> 00:26:58.420
Again, this proves
that it works.

00:26:58.420 --> 00:27:00.605
As a result, they obtained
10% better conversion.

00:27:03.130 --> 00:27:03.950
All right.

00:27:03.950 --> 00:27:06.590
The last rule is
selling umbrellas

00:27:06.590 --> 00:27:09.110
where and when it rains.

00:27:09.110 --> 00:27:12.010
It's basically not only about
what you sell, umbrellas,

00:27:12.010 --> 00:27:14.420
but when and where
you sell them.

00:27:14.420 --> 00:27:18.640
So the best way to describe
them, to describe this example,

00:27:18.640 --> 00:27:23.320
is showing you
what Playdots does.

00:27:23.320 --> 00:27:27.800
They recently redesigned their
old in-app purchase flow,

00:27:27.800 --> 00:27:30.790
and as a result they
obtained 10% better revenue

00:27:30.790 --> 00:27:32.570
per active user.

00:27:32.570 --> 00:27:35.140
So without changing
their user base,

00:27:35.140 --> 00:27:37.980
they got 10% better revenues
just by redesigning along

00:27:37.980 --> 00:27:39.500
these lines.

00:27:39.500 --> 00:27:42.630
And I'll show you
what I mean here.

00:27:42.630 --> 00:27:46.040
So the first thing, when
you start a new level,

00:27:46.040 --> 00:27:49.960
you see how many boosters
you have available for you.

00:27:49.960 --> 00:27:52.430
And they give you
one button that you

00:27:52.430 --> 00:27:55.350
can use to purchase whatever
boxes or boosters you

00:27:55.350 --> 00:27:56.760
need to finish that level.

00:27:56.760 --> 00:27:58.760
So you don't have to go
in the store in the game

00:27:58.760 --> 00:28:01.910
and buy what you think you might
need; they prompt you to buy

00:28:01.910 --> 00:28:04.760
before you start the level
exactly what you need, and they

00:28:04.760 --> 00:28:06.710
show you what you already have.

00:28:06.710 --> 00:28:09.350
Similarly, when you die
in a level-- in this case,

00:28:09.350 --> 00:28:11.382
you're running out of
movess-- they show you

00:28:11.382 --> 00:28:13.340
another call to action
that says, why don't you

00:28:13.340 --> 00:28:15.160
buy those extra five
moves that you need

00:28:15.160 --> 00:28:16.880
to finish the game, the level.

00:28:16.880 --> 00:28:18.550
So you don't have
to quit the game,

00:28:18.550 --> 00:28:23.030
go to the store in the
game, and buy what you need.

00:28:23.030 --> 00:28:24.670
You can buy it
now, without having

00:28:24.670 --> 00:28:28.820
to quit the level that you're
actually trying to finish.

00:28:28.820 --> 00:28:32.700
By only doing this, they
got 6% more paying users

00:28:32.700 --> 00:28:36.620
by just adding these
two calls to action.

00:28:36.620 --> 00:28:40.480
The other thing they did is
they moved some in-game items

00:28:40.480 --> 00:28:44.180
that you can purchase right
into the UI of the game.

00:28:44.180 --> 00:28:45.970
So again, you don't
have to quit the game.

00:28:45.970 --> 00:28:48.270
You can buy them as
you play, whenever

00:28:48.270 --> 00:28:50.070
you want, with one tap.

00:28:50.070 --> 00:28:51.180
They're always there.

00:28:51.180 --> 00:28:55.180
By doing that, they got
5% better average revenue

00:28:55.180 --> 00:28:57.840
per user.

00:28:57.840 --> 00:29:02.150
So really, it's all about making
purchasing easy, accessible,

00:29:02.150 --> 00:29:05.490
but also relevant-- positioning
those in-app purchases,

00:29:05.490 --> 00:29:08.110
those products that you're
selling, exactly where you

00:29:08.110 --> 00:29:10.460
think that the user
will need them,

00:29:10.460 --> 00:29:14.600
and triggering
calls to action when

00:29:14.600 --> 00:29:16.750
you think that those
are the most relevant

00:29:16.750 --> 00:29:21.130
so that users are more
compelled to actually purchase.

00:29:21.130 --> 00:29:25.790
The best example to show
how this works in an app

00:29:25.790 --> 00:29:29.180
environment is TomTom.

00:29:29.180 --> 00:29:31.140
Last year, they moved
from a premium model,

00:29:31.140 --> 00:29:33.600
so you just had
to pay for the app

00:29:33.600 --> 00:29:36.130
to use the app, to freemium.

00:29:36.130 --> 00:29:41.024
And in that transition, they
got 2.4 more paying users.

00:29:41.024 --> 00:29:42.940
And that's because they
thought very carefully

00:29:42.940 --> 00:29:44.940
about their business
model, and they really

00:29:44.940 --> 00:29:46.740
implemented very
well, especially

00:29:46.740 --> 00:29:50.380
along the lines of the rule
that I described to you before.

00:29:50.380 --> 00:29:52.070
This is how it looks.

00:29:52.070 --> 00:29:55.530
It's very similar to the
game I showed you before.

00:29:55.530 --> 00:29:58.867
You have 75 kilometers
to use the app for free.

00:29:58.867 --> 00:30:00.200
After that, you have to upgrade.

00:30:00.200 --> 00:30:01.908
And upgrading means
that you're basically

00:30:01.908 --> 00:30:05.420
buying what they used to
sell before as a premium app.

00:30:05.420 --> 00:30:08.580
What they did is that they
positioned that Upgrade button

00:30:08.580 --> 00:30:11.010
in the UI of the app,
and it's always there.

00:30:11.010 --> 00:30:13.670
No matter where you are,
it's always one tap away.

00:30:13.670 --> 00:30:17.600
You also see the countdown
of those free kilometers

00:30:17.600 --> 00:30:19.000
that you still have.

00:30:19.000 --> 00:30:21.930
So you also feel the urgency of
upgrading if you're running out

00:30:21.930 --> 00:30:23.450
of kilometers.

00:30:23.450 --> 00:30:25.380
Very easy, very relevant.

00:30:25.380 --> 00:30:29.740
The other thing they did is they
introduced some calls to action

00:30:29.740 --> 00:30:32.820
when they thought you would
need to upgrade the most.

00:30:32.820 --> 00:30:35.660
For example, you
start a new trip,

00:30:35.660 --> 00:30:38.400
and they know that
you will run out

00:30:38.400 --> 00:30:40.050
of kilometers during that trip.

00:30:40.050 --> 00:30:42.614
They tell you, why don't you
upgrade now instead of doing it

00:30:42.614 --> 00:30:43.530
while they're driving?

00:30:43.530 --> 00:30:45.040
You might not have a connection.

00:30:45.040 --> 00:30:48.240
So really, when you
start an activity

00:30:48.240 --> 00:30:52.080
that they know is more
likely to convert you,

00:30:52.080 --> 00:30:53.974
they prompt you to do it.

00:30:53.974 --> 00:30:56.140
Second, of course, they
show you that call to action

00:30:56.140 --> 00:30:58.765
when you're actually running out
of kilometers, or you ran out.

00:30:58.765 --> 00:31:01.420
So those little things
actually add up,

00:31:01.420 --> 00:31:04.980
and they're the ones
that really make

00:31:04.980 --> 00:31:07.620
a freemium model successful.

00:31:07.620 --> 00:31:10.460
Another example,
a bit more simple

00:31:10.460 --> 00:31:12.940
and maybe more
applicable in most cases,

00:31:12.940 --> 00:31:14.595
is the subscription example.

00:31:14.595 --> 00:31:16.970
If you sell a subscription,
normally with a subscription,

00:31:16.970 --> 00:31:20.830
you'll unlock different
features and content.

00:31:20.830 --> 00:31:23.462
And yes, you can offer
that in your app,

00:31:23.462 --> 00:31:25.170
and you can have a
list of all the things

00:31:25.170 --> 00:31:26.830
that that subscription unlocks.

00:31:26.830 --> 00:31:29.810
But also, showing the
content and the feature

00:31:29.810 --> 00:31:33.450
in the flow of the app
that are behind a pay wall,

00:31:33.450 --> 00:31:35.140
and prompting the
user to upgrade

00:31:35.140 --> 00:31:37.520
when they're actually
trying to access those,

00:31:37.520 --> 00:31:38.780
is very impactful.

00:31:38.780 --> 00:31:40.800
This is what Busuu does.

00:31:40.800 --> 00:31:43.210
It is a language-learning
app, and their subscription

00:31:43.210 --> 00:31:46.370
basically unlocks more
content and more languages.

00:31:46.370 --> 00:31:49.530
And they started putting these
calls to action with a button

00:31:49.530 --> 00:31:52.000
to actually go into
the purchase flow

00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:54.090
when you're trying to
access that content

00:31:54.090 --> 00:31:56.530
and those languages that
are behind the pay wall.

00:31:56.530 --> 00:31:59.740
And you see the result
here-- 30% better conversion

00:31:59.740 --> 00:32:03.740
with the premium content
and 83% better conversion

00:32:03.740 --> 00:32:05.830
with the languages.

00:32:05.830 --> 00:32:07.490
So very impactful.

00:32:07.490 --> 00:32:10.310
All right, to wrap up, the
three rules we talked about

00:32:10.310 --> 00:32:13.290
are climbing the
engagement cliff, which

00:32:13.290 --> 00:32:18.180
is all about focusing
on those seven days

00:32:18.180 --> 00:32:20.400
after the user has
installed the app,

00:32:20.400 --> 00:32:23.660
understanding that those are the
key moments where the user is

00:32:23.660 --> 00:32:25.220
still not comfortable
with your app,

00:32:25.220 --> 00:32:28.180
defining the activation moments
you need them to go through,

00:32:28.180 --> 00:32:30.840
and making sure that those
are presented gradually

00:32:30.840 --> 00:32:32.936
in the experience in
the first seven days

00:32:32.936 --> 00:32:34.310
so that they are
not overwhelmed,

00:32:34.310 --> 00:32:35.245
they feel a sense
of progression,

00:32:35.245 --> 00:32:37.500
they understand why they're
doing what they're doing,

00:32:37.500 --> 00:32:39.708
and they hopefully fully
unlock the value of your app

00:32:39.708 --> 00:32:42.270
so that they might stick
around for much longer.

00:32:42.270 --> 00:32:45.050
The second rule is about
embracing your app's

00:32:45.050 --> 00:32:46.780
multiple personality disorder.

00:32:46.780 --> 00:32:48.750
Freemium model is all
about lots of users

00:32:48.750 --> 00:32:52.000
wanting different things
and having different value

00:32:52.000 --> 00:32:52.860
perceptions.

00:32:52.860 --> 00:32:56.300
Being able to segment them,
understand what they want,

00:32:56.300 --> 00:33:00.910
and target them based on their
segments will help you improve

00:33:00.910 --> 00:33:04.450
your conversion in a much
more effective way than using

00:33:04.450 --> 00:33:06.260
a one-size-fits-all approach.

00:33:06.260 --> 00:33:08.480
The third rule we
talked about is

00:33:08.480 --> 00:33:11.065
selling umbrellas where
and when it rains,

00:33:11.065 --> 00:33:12.940
which means that it's
not only about what you

00:33:12.940 --> 00:33:14.960
sell, but also how you sell it.

00:33:14.960 --> 00:33:17.730
And it makes a big
difference, making sure

00:33:17.730 --> 00:33:21.340
that the in-app purchases
are presented in an easy way

00:33:21.340 --> 00:33:25.150
to access them, always at
least one or two taps away

00:33:25.150 --> 00:33:29.070
from purchasing, and also
triggering those calls

00:33:29.070 --> 00:33:31.690
to action when you think
those in-app purchases are

00:33:31.690 --> 00:33:34.000
most relevant for the user.

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:35.210
So that was it.

00:33:35.210 --> 00:33:36.160
Thank you very much.

